Three petty crimes in `src/petty.ts`, each tied to its finding type — what an agent could get wrong today, and the refactor.

## 1. `describeCheckout` — Option Bag Junk Drawer (crime_00031)

**Finding:** parameter `options` is a generic bag; the body reads six unrelated fields (`plan`, `role`, `region`, `currency`, `status`, `retry`).

**What an agent gets wrong today:** the type `CheckoutOptions` mixes identity (`plan`, `role`), locale (`region`, `currency`), and runtime state (`status`, `retry`) under one name. An agent adding a new field — say `couponCode` — has no signal whether it belongs here or whether `describeCheckout` should consume it. The function's "shape" is whatever the type happens to contain on any given day, so callers grow a kitchen-sink object that every consumer must keep in lockstep.

**Refactor:** name the actual shape this function owns — the join key — and destructure exactly those fields. Either:

```ts
type CheckoutKey = Pick<CheckoutOptions, "plan" | "role" | "region" | "currency" | "status" | "retry">;

export function describeCheckout({ plan, role, region, currency, status, retry }: CheckoutKey) {
  return [plan, role, region, currency, status, String(retry)].join(":");
}
```

Better still, split the inputs by concern (`identity`, `locale`, `state`) so adding a field forces the agent to pick where it belongs.

## 2. `resolvePaymentResult` — Return Shape Roulette (crime_00032)

**Finding:** three return branches with 0% key overlap — `{ ok, code, message }`, `{ url, permanent }`, `{ ok, value, cached }`. No declared return type.

**What an agent gets wrong today:** TypeScript infers a union, but callers can't see it from the signature, so an agent adding a fourth branch (or a caller checking `result.url`) won't know which fields are mutually exclusive. The `ok` flag exists on two branches but not the redirect one — an agent reading `if (result.ok)` will silently treat redirects as failures.

**Refactor:** name the variants as a discriminated union and annotate the return.

```ts
type PaymentResult =
  | { kind: "error"; code: string; message: string }
  | { kind: "redirect"; url: string; permanent: boolean }
  | { kind: "success"; value: string; cached: boolean };

export function resolvePaymentResult(input: PaymentInput): PaymentResult {
  if (input.error) return { kind: "error", code: input.code!, message: input.message! };
  if (input.redirect) return { kind: "redirect", url: input.url!, permanent: false };
  return { kind: "success", value: input.value!, cached: false };
}
```

Now `switch (result.kind)` is exhaustive and agents extending the function get a compile error rather than a silently wrong shape.

## 3. `canRunBilling` — Negative Flag Maze (crime_00033)

**Finding:** `if (!disableBilling && !skipRetry) return true;` — two negatives ANDed, plus the bare booleans fail the boolean-prefix detector (crime_00029).

**What an agent gets wrong today:** the function is named `canRunBilling` (positive), but its parameters are inverted (`disableBilling`, `skipRetry`). Extending the condition — e.g. adding "block on stale plan" — invites the agent to write `&& !planStale`, doubling the inversion stack. Each negation flip during maintenance is a coin toss. Worse, callers passing `disableBilling: false, skipRetry: false` to mean "yes please run billing" read backwards at every call site.

**Refactor:** flip to positive predicates and let the function be the predicate.

```ts
export function canRunBilling({ billingEnabled, retriesAllowed }: {
  billingEnabled: boolean;
  retriesAllowed: boolean;
}): boolean {
  return billingEnabled && retriesAllowed;
}
```

Callers now read `canRunBilling({ billingEnabled: true, retriesAllowed: true })` — the truth value of each flag matches the word it carries, and any future condition (`&& planActive`) extends without a double-negative.

---

**Common thread:** all three crimes are low severity individually, but each pushes the *interpretation* of intent onto the reader (or agent). The fixes don't change behaviour — they make the contract visible to the type system so the next edit fails loudly instead of silently.
